{"timestamp": "2025-12-12 20:01:38.241432", "event": "llm_end", "text": "**Short answer – the network is healthy.**  \nAll 64 ping tests returned 2 / 2 packets with 0 % loss, so every host can reach both `pc_1_2` (10.1.2.2) and `pc_0_4` (10.0.4.2).  No packet drops or time‑outs were observed.\n\n**What the numbers tell us**\n\n| Host | Destination | Avg RTT (ms) | Jitter (ms) | Notes |\n|------|-------------|--------------|-------------|-------|\n| pc_0_0 … pc_3_7 | pc_1_2 | 1.6 – 5.6 | 0.12 – 3.1 | All within a few ms of each other; the highest is 5.6 ms (pc_2_0). |\n| pc_0_0 … pc_3_7 | pc_0_4 | 1.6 – 4.1 | 0.006 – 1.6 | All within a few ms; the highest is 4.1 ms (pc_3_7). |\n\n* **No packet loss** – every ping succeeded.\n* **Low latency** – the average round‑trip times are all under 6 ms, which is well within the expected range for a local‑area network.\n* **Acceptable jitter** – the standard deviation (jitter) is generally below 1 ms; the few outliers (e.g., 2.33 ms jitter on pc_2_7 to pc_0_4) are still tiny compared to the mean RTT.\n\n**Potential “issues” that are not actually problems**\n\n* **Higher RTT on some paths** – e.g., pc_2_0 to pc_1_2 averages 5.6 ms, a bit higher than the rest of the hosts.  This is still a perfectly normal value for a multi‑hop path through a few switches; it does not indicate a failure.\n* **Occasional spikes** – a few pings show a single high RTT (e.g., 8.7 ms on pc_2_0 to pc_1_2).  These are isolated spikes and do not affect overall connectivity.\n\n**Conclusion**\n\nThe ping matrix shows a fully connected, loss‑free network.  All hosts can reach both target PCs, and the latency/jitter figures are within normal limits for a LAN.  No further troubleshooting is required at this time.", "generation_info": {"model": "gpt-oss:20b", "created_at": "2025-12-12T20:01:36.973914796Z", "done": true, "done_reason": "stop", "total_duration": 16253402971, "load_duration": 70939977, "prompt_eval_count": 8192, "prompt_eval_duration": 7366416129